Dynamic Constraint

Coppock, Alexander and Donald P. Green. Do Belief Systems Exhibit Dynamic Constraint? Working Paper.

  • Preliminary Draft
  • Donald P. Greens personal website

Abstract

As described in Converse (1964), belief systems are dynamically constrained if a change in one idea-element causes a concomitant change in a related idea-element. While an enormous literature is dedicated to the study of static constraint (the extent to which individuals hold political views that go together), very little theoretical or empirical work has developed the concept of dynamic constraint since Converses original formulation. We fill this gap with a new formalization of the theoretical argument and evidence from survey experiments conducted variously on online convenience samples, a nationally representative sample, and a convenience sample of political elites. Our results indicate that even among subjects whose belief systems are manifestly constrained in the static sense, a change in one attitude does not necessitate changes in related attitudes. We conclude that on the whole, weak levels of dynamic constraint underscore Converses thesis about the limited extent of ideological thinking in the mass public.

Figure 5 from paper, showing strong effects of treatments on target issues and virtually no effects of treatments on nontarget issues.
